e Total Force Capabilities: Could New Forms of Reserve Service Help Alleviate Military Shortfalls? -- t14 The Role of Private Military Security Companies in Counterinsurgency Operations -- t15 Cultural Aspects Facilitating and Hindering the US Department of Defense’s Integration of Private Military Contractors -- t16 US Contingency Contractors as Part of the Total Defence Force: Framing the Spectrum of Nonstate Security Actors -- t17 Business-Military Relations and Collaborative Total Defence in Scandinavia -- t18 Conclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTotal defence, as a concept, combines and extends military and civil defence: in a state of war or emergency, all social institutions mobilize to defend the state. Total defence forces, led by a diverse workforce of defence and security professionals, are critical to both national defence and international security goals.Total Defence Forces in the Twenty-First Century looks at the various groups that make up this workforce: members of the military’s regular force, reservists, defence civil servants, and contractors working for private military and security companies. When civilian staff and military personnel work towards a common goal, their distinct professional cultures and identities can make integration challenging. Despite the often high levels of partnership, underlying differences affect the quality of the collaboration and, ultimately, organizational and operational effectiveness. Defence ministries around the world are increasingly recognizing the importance of optimizing the ways in which they employ and integrate civilian and military personnel.This volume focuses on a critical question: what are the main challenges to workforce integration and collaboration, and how can such challenges be overcome to deliver the full potential of the total defence force? Together, scholars and practitioners provide some answers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArmed ForcesxReserves. 0aCivil defense. 0aCivil-military relations. 0aMilitary readiness. 0aPrivate military companies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Military Policy.2bisacsh  aDefence policy.  acontractors.  adefence civilians.  ainclusive.  aintegration.  amilitary affairs.  anational armed forces.  aprivate security.  aregular forces.  areserves.1 aBatka, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen-Ari, Eyal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen-Shalom, Uzi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerndtsson, Joakim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerndtsson, Joakim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aConnelly, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoombs, Howard G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalzell, Stephen R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFebbraro, Angela R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldenberg, Irina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldenberg, Irina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrespin, Whitney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHlatky, Stéfanie Von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHlatky, Stéfanie von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHokwerda, Femke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKasurak, Peter, econtr